# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: compressor-stall
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] On 6 December 1997, a Russian Air Force Antonov An-124-100, en route from Irkutsk Northwest Airport to Cam Ranh Air Base in Vietnam, crashed in a residential area after takeoff from the airport.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] Leased by Ukrainian Cargo Airways, the aircraft was carrying two Sukhoi Su-27UBK fighters (8524 and 8525) for delivery to the Vietnam People's Air Force, with a planned stopover at Vladivostok.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] Three seconds after lift-off from Runway 14 at Irkutsk, the No.3 engine surged at approximately 5 metres (16 ft) altitude.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] The aircraft continued to climb, but at a high angle of attack, disrupting airflow to No.1 and No.2 engines which also surged.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] Unable to continue climbing the aircraft descended until it struck houses in Mira Street, 1,600 metres (5,200 ft; 1,700 yd) beyond the runway end, killing all 23 on board and 49 persons on the ground.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] The Antonov An-124-100 aircraft that crashed was first leased by Aeroflot in 1985 with her maiden flight on 30 October 1985.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] On 14 February 1988, ownership was transferred to the Soviet Air Forces, under the 566th Military Transport Aviation Regiment, 12th Military Transport Aviation Division "Crazy Russian Girls" based in Seshcha, Bryansk Oblast airbase, with a tail number of CCCP-82005 (RA-82005).
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] On the day of the accident the Antonov had accumulated 576 takeoff/landing cycles for the Russian Air Force and had flown over 1,034 hours.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] On 6 December 1997, RA-82005 was transporting two Su-27UBK fighters with a total weight of 40 tons to Vietnam.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] At 14:42 IKT aircraft took off from Irkutsk.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] However, just three seconds after lift-off from the runway at a height of 5 metres (16 ft), there was a surge in engine number 3 which caused an increase of the angular velocity of the Antonov.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] This resulted in a shutdown of engine number 2.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] Eight seconds after takeoff at the altitude of 66 metres (217 ft), following a surge in engine number 1, the aircraft began losing altitude.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] Although the pilots had tried to maintain control over the aircraft with a single remaining functioning engine, the aircraft crashed into apartment block number 45 on Grazhdanskaya Street.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] The tail section of the Antonov significantly damaged block number 120 and a neighboring orphanage.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] The crash resulted in the deaths of all of the crew on board the aircraft as well as 49 people on the ground (including 12 children from the orphanage).
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] More than 70 families were left homeless due to the damage dealt on the two blocks by the crashed aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] The damage was aggravated by the ignition of tons of aviation fuel leaked during the crash.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] A special commission was established to investigate the causes of the disaster.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] The two flight recorders, including the cockpit voice recorder, were in the center of the fire and were too badly damaged to provide meaningful data.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] The cause of failure of the three engines was never fully confirmed and the final conclusion of the commission has not been made public.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] However, temperatures in Irkutsk were below −20 °C (−4 °F) and it was theorized that the disaster was caused by mixing cold-weather fuel with regular fuel, which was present in the tanks of An-124 after previous flight from Vietnam.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] That mix would have produced ice crystals which would clog the fuel filters, which would cut the fuel flow to the engines.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] In an interview with the *Moskovsky Komsomolets* newspaper, the test pilot Alexander Akimenkov said that the accident could have been caused by the call of a passenger with the Chinese radiotelephone, which affected how the electronics work.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] Major General Boris Tumanov, former Chief of the Russian Air Force Flight Safety Service (1993–2002) and a member of the Commission of Inquiry into Air Accidents with military aircraft, told the Moskovsky Komsomolets that the accident was caused by failure of three engines as a result of the surge.
[src:compressor-stall/1997-irkutsk-an-124-crash] In 2009, Fedor Muravchenko, General Designer of Ivchenko-Progress Design Bureau (which is the developer of aircraft engines for the An-124), gave his own version of the causes of the disaster.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:compressor-stall/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:compressor-stall/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Whilst taking off from Charles de Gaulle Airport, Air France Flight 4590 ran over debris on the runway dropped by an aircraft during the preceding departure, causing a tyre to explode and disintegrate.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Tyre fragments, launched upwards at great speed by the rapidly spinning wheel, violently struck the underside of the wing, damaging parts of the landing gear – thus preventing its retraction – and causing the integral fuel tank to rupture.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Large amounts of fuel leaking from the rupture ignited, causing a loss of thrust in the left side engines 1 and 2.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The aircraft lifted off, but the loss of thrust, high drag from the extended landing gear, and fire damage to the flight controls made it impossible to maintain control.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The jet crashed into a hotel in nearby Gonesse two minutes after takeoff.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] All nine crew and one hundred passengers on board were killed, as well as four people in the hotel.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Four other people sustained slight injuries.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] In the wake of the disaster, the entire Concorde fleet was grounded.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Following the implementation of various modifications to the airframe, it returned to service on 7 November 2001.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] However, due to limited commercial success, especially in the wake of the September 11 attacks, Concorde aircraft were retired by Air France in May 2003 and by British Airways that November.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The aircraft involved was a 25-year-old Aérospatiale-BAC Concorde (registration F-BTSC).
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] It was powered by four Rolls-Royce Olympus 593/610 turbojet engines, each of which was equipped with reheat.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The aircraft's last scheduled repair had taken place on 21 July 2000, four days before the accident; no problems were reported during the repair.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] At the time of the crash, the aircraft had flown for 11,989 hours and had made 4,873 take-off and landing cycles.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The wind at the airport was light and variable that day, and was reported to the cockpit crew as an eight-knot (15 km/h; 9 mph) tailwind as they lined up on runway 26R.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The DC-10 was not seriously affected by this.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] It did not directly puncture any of the fuel tanks, but it sent out a pressure shockwave that ruptured the number 5 fuel tank at its weakest point, just ahead of the left landing gear well.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Leaking fuel gushing out from the bottom of the wing was most likely ignited either by an electric arc in the landing gear bay (debris cutting the landing gear wire) or through contact with hot parts of the engine.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Engines 1 and 2 both surged and lost all power, likely due to ingestion of hot gases (both engines) and tyre debris (engine 1 only), and then engine 1 slowly recovered over the next few seconds.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] A large plume of flame developed, and the flight engineer shut down engine 2 in response to a fire warning and the captain's command.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Air traffic controller Gilles Logelin noticed the flames before the Concorde was airborne and informed the flight crew.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] However, the aircraft had passed V1 speed, at which point takeoff is considered unsafe to abort.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The plane did not gain enough airspeed with the three remaining engines as damage to the landing gear bay door prevented the retraction of the undercarriage.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The aircraft was unable to climb or accelerate, and its speed decayed during the course of its brief flight.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The fire damaged the inner elevon of the left wing and it began to disintegrate, melted by the extremely high temperatures.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Engine number 1 surged again, but did not fully recover, and the right wing lifted from the asymmetrical thrust, banking the aircraft to over 100 degrees.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The crew reduced the power on engines three and four in an attempt to level the aircraft, but they lost control due to deceleration and the aircraft stalled.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The aircraft struck the ground left wing low after a heading change of nearly 180°, crashing into the Hôtelissimo Les Relais Bleus Hotel.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] A video of the burning plane on takeoff and the aftermath of the crash was captured by a passenger in a passing truck.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The crew tried to divert to nearby Paris–Le Bourget Airport, but accident investigators stated that a safe landing would have been highly unlikely, given the aircraft's flightpath.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The flight was chartered by German company Peter Deilmann Cruises.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The passengers were on their way to board the cruise ship MS *Deutschland* in New York for a 16-day cruise to Manta, Ecuador.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] They included German football manager Rudi Faßnacht and German trade union board member Christian Götz.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] All the passengers and crew, as well as four employees of the Hotelissimo hotel, were killed in the crash.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] A few days after the crash, all Air France Concordes were grounded, pending an investigation into the cause of the crash and possible remedies.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] British Airways grounded their Concordes three weeks later for the same reason.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Air France's Concorde operation had been a money-losing venture, and it is claimed that the aeroplane had been kept in service as a matter of national pride; British Airways claimed to make a profit on its Concorde operations.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] According to Jock Lowe, a Concorde pilot, until the crash of Air France Flight 4590 at Paris, the British Airways Concorde operation made a net average profit of about £30M (equivalent to £54M in 2024) a year.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Commercial service was resumed on 7 November 2001, after a £17M (£30M in 2024) safety improvement programme, until the type was retired between May (Air France) and October (British Airways), 2003.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] This was the only fatal accident of Concorde's entire service life.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The official investigation was conducted by France's accident investigation bureau, the Bureau of Enquiry and Analysis for Civil Aviation Safety (BEA) and led by chief investigator Alain Bouillard.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Post-accident investigation revealed that the aircraft was over the maximum takeoff weight for ambient temperature and other conditions, and 810 kg (1,790 lb) over the maximum structural weight, loaded so that the centre of gravity was aft of the take-off limit.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Fuel transfer during taxiing left the number 5 wing tank 94 percent full.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] A 30-centimetre (12 in) spacer normally keeps the left main landing gear in alignment, but it had not been replaced after recent maintenance; the BEA concluded that this did not contribute to the accident.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The final report was issued on 16 January 2002.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Former British Airways Concorde captain John Hutchinson said the fire on its own should have been 'eminently survivable; the pilot should have been able to fly his way out of trouble'.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Hutchinson believed this did not happen due to a series of operational errors and 'negligence' by the maintenance department.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] While examining the wreckage in a warehouse, investigators noticed that a spacer was missing from the bogie beam on the left-hand main landing gear.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] (It was later found in an Air France maintenance workshop.) This skewed the alignment of the landing gear because a strut was able to wobble in any direction with 3° of movement.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The problem was exacerbated on the left gear's three remaining tyres by the uneven fuel load.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Drag marks left on the runway by the left rear landing wheels show the Concorde was veering to the left as it accelerated toward takeoff.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Photographs in the BEA report showed a smashed steel landing light, clipped by the aircraft, parts of which were probably ingested by engine number 1.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] According to Rose, former French Concorde pilot Jean-Marie Chauve and former Concorde flight engineer Michel Suaud spent six months preparing a 60-page report which was submitted to the investigating judge.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] They re-evaluated two factors that the BEA had found to be of negligible consequence to the crash, the unbalanced weight distribution in the fuel tanks and the loose landing gear.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] At the start of the takeoff, the aircraft had 1.2 tonnes of extra fuel which should have been burnt during the aircraft's taxi.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Nineteen items of luggage, weighing some 500 kg (0.5 tonnes) were loaded onto the aircraft at the last minute without being included in the aircraft's manifest, giving the aircraft a weight of 186 tonnes, which exceeded the aircraft's certified maximum structural weight by 1 tonne.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] A change in wind conditions created an 8-knot tailwind, which would have reduced the regulated takeoff weight to 180 tonnes, 6 tonnes below the actual aircraft weight.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Rather than taking off from the other end of the runway, in order to take off into the wind, no change in takeoff direction occurred.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The additional weight of the extra fuel in tank 11, the rearmost tank, plus the additional luggage shifted the aircraft's centre of gravity rearwards, to beyond the safe operating limit of 54 percent, set by the Concorde test pilots.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Once the damaged forward tank 5 began to lose fuel, the centre of gravity moved even further rearward.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] At one point, it drifted toward a just-landed Air France Boeing 747 that was carrying then-French President Jacques Chirac (who was returning from the 26th G8 summit meeting in Okinawa, Japan).
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] As the plane was about to leave the runway, with the aircraft rotated for takeoff, its speed was only 188 knots, 11 knots under the minimum recommended velocity.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The flight engineer shut down engine number two at only 25 feet altitude.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The procedure for shutting down an engine is to wait until stable flight at 400 feet is achieved, and then only on the command of the captain.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] In November 1981, the American National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) sent a letter of concern to the French BEA that included safety recommendations for Concorde.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] This communiqué was the result of the NTSB's investigations of four Air France Concorde incidents during a 20-month period from July 1979 to February 1981.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The NTSB described those incidents as "potentially catastrophic", because they were caused by blown tyres during takeoff.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] During its 27 years in service, Concorde had about 70 tyre- or wheel-related incidents, seven of which caused serious damage to the aircraft or were potentially catastrophic.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Because it is a tailless delta-wing aircraft, Concorde could not use the normal flaps or slats to assist takeoff and landing, and required a significantly higher air and tyre speed during the takeoff roll than an average airliner.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] That higher speed increased the risk of tyre burst during takeoff.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Analysis of test results revealed that this occurring could release sufficient kinetic energy to cause the fuel tank to rupture.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The analysis of impact energy considered a tyre piece of 4.5 kilograms (9.9 lb) with a speed around 140 metres per second (310 mph).
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The piece could reach this speed by combination of rotation of the tyre on takeoff and the tyre burst.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The accident led to modifications to Concorde, including more-secure electrical controls, Kevlar lining to the fuel tanks, and specially developed burst-resistant tyres.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The crash of the Air France Concorde nonetheless proved to be the beginning of the end for the type.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Just before service resumed, the September 11 attacks took place, resulting in a marked drop in passenger numbers, and contributing to the eventual end of Concorde flights.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Air France stopped flights in May 2003, followed by British Airways five months later.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] In June 2010, two groups attempted, unsuccessfully, to revive Concorde for "Heritage" flights in time for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The British Save Concorde Group, SCG, and French group Olympus 593 were attempting to obtain four Rolls-Royce Olympus engines from the Le Bourget Air and Space Museum.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Continental denied the charges, and claimed in court that it was being used as a scapegoat by the BEA.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The airline suggested that the Concorde "was already on fire when its wheels hit the titanium strip, and that around 20 first-hand witnesses had confirmed that the plane seemed to be on fire immediately after it began its take-off roll".
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] At the same time, charges were laid against Henri Perrier, head of the Concorde program at Aérospatiale; Jacques Hérubel, Concorde's chief engineer; and Claude Frantzen, head of DGAC, the French airline regulator.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] It was alleged that Perrier, Hérubel, and Frantzen knew that the plane's fuel tanks could be susceptible to damage from foreign objects, but nonetheless allowed it to fly.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The trial ran in a Parisian court from February to December 2010.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Continental Airlines was found criminally responsible for the disaster.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Taylor was given a 15-month suspended sentence, while Ford, Perrier, Hérubel, and Frantzen were cleared of all charges.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The court ruled that the crash resulted from a piece of metal from a Continental jet that was left on the runway; the object punctured a tyre on the Concorde and then ruptured a fuel tank.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The convictions were overturned by a French appeals court in November 2012, thereby clearing Continental (which had merged with United Airlines by then) and Taylor of criminal responsibility.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The Parisian court also ruled that Continental would have to pay 70% of any compensation claims.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] As Air France had paid out €100 million to the families of the victims, Continental could be made to pay its share of that compensation payout.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The French appeals court, while overturning the criminal rulings by the Parisian court, affirmed the civil ruling and left Continental liable for the compensation claims.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] A monument in honour of the crash victims was established at Gonesse.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] The Gonesse monument consists of a piece of transparent glass with a piece of an aircraft wing jutting through.
[src:compressor-stall/air-france-flight-4590] Another monument, a 6,000-square-metre (65,000 sq ft) memorial surrounded with topiary planted in the shape of a Concorde, was established in 2006 at Mitry-Mory, just south of Charles de Gaulle Airport.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:compressor-stall/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:compressor-stall/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] An **aircraft carrier** is a warship designed to carry, launch, recover and support aircraft at sea, equipped with a full-length flight deck and hangar facilities that allow it to serve as a mobile, seagoing airbase.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Typically it is the capital ship of a fleet (known as a carrier battle group), as it allows a naval force to project seaborne air power far from national territory without depending on local airfields for the staging of aircraft operations.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] While heavier fixed-wing aircraft such as airlifters, gunships and bombers have been launched from aircraft carriers, these aircraft do not often land on a carrier due to flight deck limitations.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier, along with its onboard aircraft and defensive ancillary weapons, is the largest weapon system ever created.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] By their tactical prowess, mobility, autonomy and the variety of operational means, aircraft carriers are often the centerpiece of modern naval warfare, and have significant diplomatic influence in deterrence, command of the sea and air supremacy.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the Second World War, the aircraft carrier has replaced the battleship in the role of flagship of a fleet, and largely transformed naval battles from gunfire to beyond-visual-range air strikes.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies use several variants of the aircraft carrier, sometimes categorized as sub-types of aircraft carriers and sometimes as distinct types of aviation-capable ships.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft carriers may be classified according to the type of aircraft they carry and their operational assignments.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Navies have a variety of classification systems for their ships, and a definitive number of current aircraft carriers depends on the specific criteria.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] As of July 2026 there are 9 navies operating 24 active vessels designated by their respective navies as either an "Aircraft Carrier" or "Aircraft Cruiser".
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] These range in tonnage from the United States' 100,000 tonne USS *Gerald R.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford* to Brazil's 21,000 tonne NAM *Atlantico*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of the types listed here are not strictly defined as aircraft carriers by some sources.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] A fleet carrier is intended to operate with the main fleet and usually provides an offensive capability.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] These are the largest carriers capable of fast speeds.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] By comparison, escort carriers were developed to provide defense for convoys of ships.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] They were smaller and slower with lower numbers of aircraft carried.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Most were built from mercantile hulls or, in the case of merchant aircraft carriers, were bulk cargo ships with a flight deck added on top.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Light aircraft carriers were fast enough to operate with the main fleet but of smaller size with reduced aircraft capacity.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Soviet aircraft carrier *Admiral Kusnetsov* was termed a "heavy aircraft-carrying cruiser".
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was primarily a legal construct to avoid the limitations of the Montreux Convention preventing 'aircraft carriers' transiting the Turkish Straits between the Soviet Black Sea bases and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] These ships, while sized in the range of large fleet carriers, were designed to deploy alone or with escorts.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition to supporting fighter aircraft and helicopters, they provide both strong defensive weaponry and heavy offensive missiles equivalent to a guided-missile cruiser.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The appellation "supercarrier" is not an official designation with any national navy, but a term used predominantly by the media and typically when reporting on larger and more advanced carrier types.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] It is also used when comparing carriers of various sizes and capabilities, both current and past.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] It was first used by *The New York Times* in 1938, in an article about the Royal Navy's HMS *Ark Royal*, that had a length of 800 feet (244 m), a displacement of 22,000 tons and was designed to carry 72 aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since then, aircraft carriers have consistently grown in size, both in length and displacement, as well as improved capabilities; in defense, sensors, electronic warfare, propulsion, range, launch and recovery systems, number and types of aircraft carried and number of sorties flown per day.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first aircraft carrier over 80,000 tonnes full-load displacement was the USS Forrestal launched in 1954.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] In total, the US Navy has had 5 different classes of aircraft carrier of this size definition, the Forrestal class, Kitty Hawk class, the Enterprise class, the Nimitz class and Gerald R Ford Class, two of which were conventional steam-powered and three nuclear-powered.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] USS *Enterprise*, launched in 1960, was the first carrier over 90,000 tonnes full load displacement and *Nimitz*, launched in 1972, was the first over 100,000 tonnes displacement.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] A total of 22 supercarriers have been launched by the US Navy since 1954, with 11 currently in service.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Both China (Type 003) and the United Kingdom (Queen Elizabeth class) have carriers in service with displacements from 80,000 to 85,000 tonnes and lengths from 280 to 320 meters (920 to 1,050 ft) which are described as "supercarriers".
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] France is also developing a new aircraft carrier (PANG) which is to have a full load displacement of 80,000 tonnes and will be considered a supercarrier.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The largest supercarrier in service as of 2024 is the US Navy's USS Gerald R.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford, with full load displacement of around 100,000 tons, length of 337 meters (1,106 ft) and capabilities that exceed those of any other class.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] A US Navy proposal for an aircraft carrier concept with a length of 1,310 feet and a displacement of 500,000 tons full load at a cost of $828 million in 1976 dollars.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Project Habakkuk could be considered an early proposal for an "ultracarrier".
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Several systems of identification symbol for aircraft carriers and related types of ship have been used.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] These include the pennant numbers used by the Royal Navy, Commonwealth countries, and Europe, along with the hull classification symbols used by the US and Canada.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Two months later, on 18 January 1911, Ely landed his Curtiss Pusher airplane on a platform on the armored cruiser USS *Pennsylvania* anchored in San Francisco Bay.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seaplane tender support ships came next, with the French *Foudre* of 1911.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Early in World War I, the Imperial Japanese Navy ship *Wakamiya* conducted the world's first carrier-launched air raid: on 6 September 1914, the *Wakamiya* used its crane to lower Farman seaplanes into the water.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Wakamiya* attacked the Austro-Hungarian cruiser SMS *Kaiserin Elisabeth* and the Imperial German gunboat *Jaguar* in Jiaozhou Bay off Qingdao; neither was hit.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first attack using an air-launched torpedo occurred on 2 August, when a torpedo was fired by Flight Commander Charles Edmonds from a Short Type 184 seaplane, launched from the seaplane carrier HMS *Ben-my-Chree*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first carrier-launched airstrike was the Tondern raid in July 1918.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seven Sopwith Camels were launched from the battlecruiser HMS *Furious*, which had been completed as a carrier by replacing her planned forward turret with a flight deck and hangar prior to commissioning.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Camels attacked and damaged the German airbase at Tondern, Germany (modern day Tønder, Denmark), and destroyed two zeppelin airships.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first landing of an airplane on a moving ship was by Squadron Commander Edwin Harris Dunning, when he landed his Sopwith Pup on HMS *Furious* in Scapa Flow, Orkney, on 2 August 1917.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Landing on the forward flight deck required the pilot to approach round the ship's superstructure, a difficult and dangerous manoeuver, and Dunning was later killed when his airplane was thrown overboard while attempting another landing on *Furious*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] HMS *Furious* was modified again when her rear turret was removed and another flight deck added over a second hangar for landing aircraft over the stern.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Her funnel and superstructure remained intact, however, and turbulence from the funnel and superstructure was severe enough that only three landing attempts were successful before further attempts were forbidden.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This experience prompted the development of vessels with a flush deck and produced the first large fleet ships.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] In 1918, HMS *Argus* became the world's first carrier capable of launching and recovering naval aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] As a result of the Washington Naval Treaty of 1922, which limited the construction of new heavy surface combat ships, most early aircraft carriers were conversions of ships that were laid down (or had served) as different ship types: cargo ships, cruisers, battlecruisers, or battleships.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] These conversions gave rise to the USS *Langley* in 1922, the US *Lexington*-class aircraft carriers (1927), Japanese *Akagi* and *Kaga*, and British *Courageous* class (of which *Furious* was one).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Specialist carrier evolution was well underway, with several navies ordering and building warships that were purposefully designed to function as aircraft carriers by the mid-1920s.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This resulted in the commissioning of ships such as the Japanese *Hōshō* (1922), HMS *Hermes* (1924, although laid down in 1918 before *Hōshō*), and *Béarn* (1927).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] During World War II, these ships would become known as fleet carriers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier dramatically changed naval warfare in World War II, because air power was becoming a significant factor in warfare.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The advent of aircraft as focal weapons was driven by the superior range, flexibility, and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] They had greater range and precision than naval guns, making them highly effective.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The versatility of the carrier was demonstrated in November 1940, when HMS *Illustrious* launched a long-range strike on the Italian fleet at their base in Taranto, signalling the beginning of the effective and highly mobile aircraft strikes.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This operation in the shallow water harbor incapacitated three of the six anchored battleships at a cost of two torpedo bombers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] World War II in the Pacific Ocean involved clashes between aircraft carrier fleets.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Japanese surprise attack on the American Pacific fleet at Pearl Harbor naval and air bases on Sunday, 7 December 1941, was a clear illustration of the power projection capability afforded by a large force of modern carriers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Concentrating six carriers in a single unit turned naval history about, as no other nation had fielded anything comparable.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] In the "Doolittle Raid", on 18 April 1942, the US Navy carrier USS *Hornet* sailed to within 650 nautical miles (1,200 km) of Japan and launched 16 B-25 Mitchell medium bombers from her deck in a demonstrative retaliatory strike on the mainland, including the capital, Tokyo.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] However, the vulnerability of carriers compared to traditional capital ships was illustrated by the sinking of HMS *Glorious* by German battleships during the Norwegian campaign in 1940.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This new-found importance of naval aviation forced nations to create a number of carriers, in efforts to provide air superiority cover for every major fleet to ward off enemy aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This extensive usage led to the development and construction of 'light' carriers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Escort aircraft carriers, such as USS *Bogue*, were sometimes purpose-built but most were converted from merchant ships as a stop-gap measure to provide anti-submarine air support for convoys and amphibious invasions.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following this concept, light aircraft carriers built by the US, such as USS *Independence* (commissioned in 1943), represented a larger, more "militarized" version of the escort carrier.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although with similar complement to escort carriers, they had the advantage of speed from their converted cruiser hulls.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The UK 1942 Design Light Fleet Carrier was designed for building quickly by civilian shipyards and with an expected service life of about 3 years.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] They served the Royal Navy during the war, and the hull design was chosen for nearly all aircraft carrier equipped navies after the war, until the 1980s.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Emergencies also spurred the creation or conversion of highly unconventional aircraft carriers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] CAM ships were cargo-carrying merchant ships that could launch (but not retrieve) a single fighter aircraft from a catapult to defend the convoy from long range land-based German aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Noteworthy converted carriers were also USS *Sable* (IX-81) and USS *Wolverine* (IX-64) that both operated on the Great Lakes for training duties and were converted from paddle steamers, making them the only aircraft carriers with this type of propulsion.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before World War II, international naval treaties of 1922, 1930, and 1936 limited the size of capital ships, including carriers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since World War II, aircraft carrier designs have increased in size to accommodate a steady increase in aircraft size.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The large, modern *Nimitz* class of US Navy carriers has a displacement nearly four times that of the World War II–era USS *Enterprise*, yet its complement of aircraft is roughly the same—a consequence of the steadily increasing size and weight of individual military aircraft over the years.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Today's aircraft carriers are so expensive that some nations which operate them risk significant economic and military impact if a carrier is lost.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies that operate such aircraft carriers treat them as capital ships of fleets, a role previously held by the galleons, ships-of-the-line and battleships.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This change took place during World War II in response to air power becoming a significant factor in warfare, driven by the superior range, flexibility and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following the war, carrier operations continued to increase in size and importance, and along with, carrier designs also increased in size and ability.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of these larger carriers, dubbed by the media as "supercarriers", displacing 75,000 tons or greater, have become the pinnacle of carrier development.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some are powered by nuclear reactors and form the core of a fleet designed to operate far from home.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Amphibious assault ships, such as the *Wasp* and *Mistral* classes, serve the purpose of carrying and landing Marines, and operate a large contingent of helicopters for that purpose.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Also known as "commando carriers" or "helicopter carriers", many have the capability to operate VSTOL aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The threatening role of aircraft carriers has a place in modern asymmetric warfare, like the gunboat diplomacy of the past.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers also facilitate quick and precise projections of overwhelming military power into such local and regional conflicts.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Lacking the firepower of other warships, carriers by themselves are considered vulnerable to attack by other ships, aircraft, submarines, or missiles.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The resulting group of ships is often termed a carrier strike group, battle group, carrier group, or carrier battle group.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] There is a view among some military pundits that modern anti-ship weapons systems, such as torpedoes and missiles, or even ballistic missiles with nuclear warheads have made aircraft carriers and carrier groups too vulnerable for modern combat.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers are large and long ships, although there is a high degree of variation depending on their intended role and aircraft complement.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The size of the carrier has varied over history and among navies, to cater to the various roles that global climates have demanded from naval aviation.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Regardless of size, the ship itself must house their complement of aircraft, with space for launching, storing, and maintaining them.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Space is also required for the large crew, supplies (food, munitions, fuel, engineering parts), and propulsion.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] US and French aircraft carriers are notable for having nuclear reactors powering their systems and propulsion.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The top of the carrier is the flight deck, where aircraft are launched and recovered.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the starboard side of this is the island, where ship navigation from the bridge and air traffic control from flyco are controlled and (in non-nuclear powered vessels), provides the location of the ship's funnel(s).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Queen Elizabeth*-class has two island structures; the forward island contains the navigation bridge, while the aft structure houses flyco.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The constraints of constructing a flight deck strongly affect the role of a given carrier, as they influence the weight, type, and configuration of the aircraft that may be launched.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, assisted launch mechanisms are used primarily for heavy aircraft, especially those loaded with air-to-ground weapons.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR is most commonly used on US Navy fleet carriers as it allows the deployment of heavy jets with full load-outs, especially on ground-attack missions.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] STOVL is used by other navies because it is cheaper to operate and still provides good deployment capability for fighter aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Due to the busy nature of the flight deck, only 20 or so aircraft may be on it at any one time.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] A hangar storage several decks below the flight deck is where most aircraft are kept, and aircraft are taken from the lower storage decks to the flight deck through the use of an elevator.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The hangar is usually quite large and can take up several decks of vertical space.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Munitions are commonly stored on the lower decks because they are highly explosive.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Usually this is below the waterline so that the area can be flooded in case of emergency.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] As "runways at sea", aircraft carriers have a flat-top flight deck, which launches and recovers aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft launch forward, into the wind, and are recovered from astern.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Creating such a surface at sea poses constraints on the carrier.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the size of the vessel is a fundamental limitation on runway length.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This affects take-off procedure, as a shorter runway length of the deck requires that aircraft accelerate more quickly to gain lift.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This either requires a thrust boost, a vertical component to its velocity, or a reduced take-off load (to lower mass).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The differing types of deck configuration, as above, influence the structure of the flight deck.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The form of launch assistance a carrier provides is strongly related to the types of aircraft embarked and the design of the carrier itself.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are two main philosophies to keep the deck short: add thrust to the aircraft, such as using a Catapult Assisted Take-Off (CATO-); and changing the direction of the airplanes' thrust, as in Vertical and/or Short Take-Off (V/STO-).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the recovery side of the flight deck, the adaptation to the aircraft load-out is mirrored.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Non-VTOL or conventional aircraft cannot decelerate on their own, and almost all carriers using them must have arrested-recovery systems (-BAR, e.g.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR or STOBAR) to recover their aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft that are landing extend a tailhook that catches on arrestor wires stretched across the deck to bring themselves to a stop in a short distance.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] If the aircraft are VTOL-capable or helicopters, they do not need to decelerate and hence there is no such need.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The arrested-recovery system has used an angled deck since the 1950s because, in case the aircraft does not catch the arresting wire, the short deck allows easier take off by reducing the number of objects between the aircraft and the end of the runway.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] It also has the advantage of separating the recovery operation area from the launch area.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Helicopters and aircraft capable of vertical or short take-off and landing (V/STOL) usually recover by coming abreast of the carrier on the port side and then using their hover capability to move over the flight deck and land vertically without the need for arresting gear.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers steam at speed, up to 35 knots (65 km/h; 40 mph) into the wind during flight deck operations to increase wind speed over the deck to a safe minimum.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This increase in effective wind speed provides a higher launch airspeed for aircraft at the end of the catapult stroke or ski-jump, as well as making recovery safer by reducing the difference between the relative speeds of the aircraft and ship.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the early 1950s on conventional carriers it has been the practice to recover aircraft at an angle to port of the axial line of the ship.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The primary function of this angled deck is to allow aircraft that miss the arresting wires, referred to as a bolter, to become airborne again without the risk of hitting aircraft parked forward.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The angled deck allows the installation of one or two "waist" catapults in addition to the two bow cats.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] An angled deck also improves launch and recovery cycle flexibility with the option of simultaneous launching and recovery of aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Conventional ("tailhook") aircraft rely upon a landing signal officer (LSO, radio call sign 'paddles') to monitor the aircraft's approach, visually gauge glideslope, attitude, and airspeed, and transmit that data to the pilot.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before the angled deck emerged in the 1950s, LSOs used colored paddles to signal corrections to the pilot (hence the nickname).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] From the late 1950s onward, visual landing aids such as the optical landing system have provided information on proper glide slope, but LSOs still transmit voice calls to approaching pilots by radio.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Key personnel involved in the flight deck include the shooters, the handler, and the air boss.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Shooters are naval aviators or naval flight officers and are responsible for launching aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The handler works just inside the island from the flight deck and is responsible for the movement of aircraft before launching and after recovery.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The captain of the ship spends most of his time one level below primary on the Navigation Bridge.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Below this is the Flag Bridge, designated for the embarked admiral and his staff.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] To facilitate working on the flight deck of a US aircraft carrier, the sailors wear colored shirts that designate their responsibilities.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are at least seven different colors worn by flight deck personnel for modern United States Navy carrier air operations.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carrier operations of other nations use similar color schemes.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The superstructure of a carrier (such as the bridge, flight control tower) are concentrated in a relatively small area called an *island*, a feature pioneered on HMS *Hermes* in 1923.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] While the island is usually built on the starboard side of the flight deck, the Japanese aircraft carriers *Akagi* and *Hiryū* had their islands built on the port side.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Very few carriers have been designed or built without an island.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *flush deck* configuration proved to have significant drawbacks, primary of which was management of the exhaust from the power plant.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Fumes coming across the deck were a major issue in USS *Langley*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition, lack of an island meant difficulties managing the flight deck, performing air traffic control, a lack of radar housing placements and problems with navigating and controlling the ship itself.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another deck structure that can be seen is a ski-jump ramp at the forward end of the flight deck.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was first developed to help launch short take off vertical landing (STOVL) aircraft take off at far higher weights than is possible with a vertical or rolling takeoff on flat decks.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Originally developed by the Royal Navy, it since has been adopted by many navies for smaller carriers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski-jump ramp works by converting some of the forward rolling movement of the aircraft into vertical velocity and is sometimes combined with the aiming of jet thrust partly downward.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] This allows heavily loaded and fueled aircraft a few more precious seconds to attain sufficient air velocity and lift to sustain normal flight.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Without a ski-jump, launching fully-loaded and fueled aircraft such as the Harrier would not be possible on a smaller flat deck ship before either stalling out or crashing directly into the sea.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although STOVL aircraft are capable of taking off vertically from a spot on the deck, using the ramp and a running start is far more fuel efficient and permits a heavier launch weight.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] As catapults are unnecessary, carriers with this arrangement reduce weight, complexity, and space needed for complex steam or electromagnetic launching equipment.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Vertical landing aircraft also remove the need for arresting cables and related hardware.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Russian, Chinese, and Indian carriers include a ski-jump ramp for launching lightly loaded conventional fighter aircraft but recover using traditional carrier arresting cables and a tailhook on their aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the Russian Sukhoi Su-33 is only able to launch from the carrier *Admiral Kuznetsov* with a minimal armament and fuel load.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another disadvantage is on mixed flight deck operations where helicopters are also present, such as on a US landing helicopter dock or landing helicopter assault amphibious assault ship.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski jump is not included as this would eliminate one or more helicopter landing areas; this flat deck limits the loading of Harriers but is somewhat mitigated by the longer rolling start provided by a long flight deck compared to many STOVL carriers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United States operates 11 nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carriers, with a total combined deck space over twice that of all other nations combined as of 2016.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] China operates one catapult-assisted aircraft carrier and two ski-jump carriers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United Kingdom and India each currently operate two ski-jump aircraft carriers, and France operates one nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carrier.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Russia deploys one ski-jump carrier, although it has not been operational since 2017.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the US operates nine large amphibious assault ships with the capability to launch vertical/short takeoff and landing (V/STOL) aircraft, and China operates four amphibious assault ships of a similar size as helicopter carriers.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Italy operates two light V/STOL carriers, and both Spain and Iran operate one V/STOL aircraft-carrying assault ship.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Helicopter carriers are also operated by Japan (4, two converting to operate V/STOL fighters) France (3), Australia (2), Egypt (2), South Korea (2), Thailand (1), Brazil (1) and Iran (1).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Future aircraft carriers are under construction or planned by China, France, India, Italy, Russia, South Korea, and the US.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Royal Australian Navy operates two *Canberra*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two-ship class, based on the Spanish vessel *Juan Carlos I* and built by Navantia and BAE Systems Australia, represents the largest ships ever built for the Royal Australian Navy.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMAS *Canberra* underwent sea trials in late 2013 and was commissioned in 2014.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Her sister ship, HMAS *Adelaide*, was commissioned in December 2015.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Australian ships retain the ski-ramp from the *Juan Carlos I* design, although the RAN has not acquired carrier-based fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2017, the Brazilian Navy confirmed the purchase of HMS *Ocean* for (GBP) £84.6 million (equivalent to R$359.5M and US$113.2M) and renamed her *Atlântico*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship was decommissioned from Royal Navy service in March 2018.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Brazilian Navy commissioned the carrier on 29 June 2018 in the United Kingdom.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] After undertaking a period of maintenance in the UK, the ship travelled to its new home port, Rio de Janeiro Navy Arsenal (AMRJ) to be fully operational by 2020.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Before leaving HMNB Devonport for her new homeport in Rio's AMRJ, *Atlântico* underwent operational sea training under the Royal Navy's Flag Officer Sea Training (FOST) program.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] China has had a long-term plan to operate six large aircraft carriers with two carriers per fleet.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is planning a class of eight LHD vessels, the Type 075 (NATO reporting name Yushen-class landing helicopter assault).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] This is a class of amphibious assault ship under construction by the Hudong–Zhonghua Shipbuilding company.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first ship was commissioned in April 2021.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is also planning a modified class of the same concept, the Type 076 landing helicopter dock, that will be equipped with an electromagnetic catapult system and will likely support launching unmanned combat aerial vehicles.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Egypt signed a contract with French shipbuilder DCNS to buy two *Mistral*-class helicopter carriers for approximately 950 million euros.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two ships were originally to be sold to Russia, but the deal was cancelled by France due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2014.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 2 June 2016, Egypt received the first of two helicopter carriers acquired in October 2015, the landing helicopter dock *Gamal Abdel Nasser*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The flag transfer ceremony took place in the presence of Egyptian and French Navies' chiefs of staff, chairman and chief executive officers of both DCNS and STX France, and senior Egyptian and French officials.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 16 September 2016, DCNS delivered the second of two helicopter carriers, the landing helicopter dock *Anwar El Sadat* which also participated in a joint military exercise with the French Navy before arriving at her home port of Alexandria.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The French Navy operates the 42,000-tonne nuclear-powered aircraft carrier, *Charles de Gaulle*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Commissioned in 2001, she is the flagship of the French Navy.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship carries a complement of Dassault Rafale M and E-2C Hawkeye aircraft, EC725 Caracal and AS532 Cougar helicopters for combat search and rescue, as well as modern electronics and Aster missiles.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] She is a CATOBAR-type carrier that uses two 75 m C13-3 steam catapults of a shorter version of the catapult system installed on the US *Nimitz*-class carriers, one catapult at the bow and one across the front of the landing area.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the French Navy operates three *Mistral*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In October 2018, the French Ministry of Defence began an 18-month €40 million study for the replacement of the French aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* sometime after 2030.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, President Macron announced that construction of the next generation carrier would begin in around 2025 with sea trials to start in about 2036.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is planned to have a displacement of around 75,000 tons and to carry about 32 next-generation fighters, two to three E-2D Advanced Hawkeyes and a yet-to-be-determined number of unmanned carrier air vehicles.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has plans for a third carrier, INS *Vishal*, also known as *Indigenous Aircraft Carrier 2 (IAC-2)* with a displacement of over 65,000 tonnes and is planned with a CATOBAR system to launch and recover heavier aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has also issued a request for information (RFI) to procure four Landing helicopter dock displacing 30,000–40,000 tons with a capacity to operate 12 medium lift special ops and two heavy lift helicopters and troops for amphibious operations.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] On February 6, 2025, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) accepted the IRIS *Shahid Bagheri*, a 41,978-tonne drone UAV carrier converted from a container ship.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] was launched August 2013 and commissioned March 2015.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] the Japanese defense ministry's position is "We are not creating carrier air wings or carrier air squadrons" similar to the US Navy.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] from land bases; according to the 2020 Japanese Defense Ministry white paper the STOVL model was chosen for the JASDF due the lack of appropriately long runways to support air superiority capability across all of Japanese airspace.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] ships "for cooperation and advice on how to operate the fighter on the deck of the modified ships".
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] , marking 75 years since fixed-wing aircraft operated from a Japanese carrier.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Portuguese Navy plans, for the second half of 2026, to receive the NRP *D.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] João II*, a platform ship capable of operating aerial, surface and underwater drones, medium helicopters (Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk) and heavy helicopters (EH101 Merlin) helicopters of the Portuguese Air Force.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] One STOBAR carrier: *Admiral Flota Sovetskogo Soyuza Kuznetsov*: 55,000-tonne *Kuznetsov*-class STOBAR aircraft carrier.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Launched in 1985 as *Tbilisi*, renamed and operational from 1995.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Without catapults she can launch and recover lightly fueled naval fighters for air defense or anti-ship missions but not heavy conventional bombing strikes.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Officially designated an aircraft carrying cruiser, she is unique in carrying a heavy cruiser's complement of defensive weapons and large P-700 Granit offensive missiles.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The P-700 systems will be removed in the coming refit to enlarge her below decks aviation facilities as well as upgrading her defensive systems.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship has been out of service and in repairs since 2018.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The most recent projection stated that repairs would be completed and the ship transferred back to the Russian Navy sometime in 2024, however this projection has not been met as of July 2025, and no updates have been provided.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Russian government has been considering the potential replacement of *Admiral Kuznetsov* for some time and has considered the Shtorm-class aircraft carrier as a possible option.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] This carrier will be a hybrid of CATOBAR and STOBAR, given the fact that she uses both systems of launching aircraft.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is expected to cost between $1.8 billion and $5.63 billion.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2020, the project had not yet been approved and, given the financial costs, it was unclear whether it would be made a priority over other elements of Russian naval modernization.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] A class of 2 LHD, Project 23900 is planned and an official keel laying ceremony for the project happened on 20 July 2020.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two *Dokdo*-class 18,860-tonne full deck amphibious assault ships with hospital and well deck and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] South Korea had set tentative plans for procuring two light aircraft carriers by 2033, which would help make the ROKN a blue water navy.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, details of South Korea's planned carrier program (CVX) were finalized.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] A vessel of about 40,000 tons is envisaged carrying about 20 F-35B fighters as well as future maritime attack helicopters.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Service entry had been anticipated in the early 2030s.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In 2025 the program was cancelled and replaced with a drone carrier program.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] One offshore helicopter support ship: HTMS *Chakri Naruebet* helicopter carrier: 11,400-tonne STOVL carrier based on Spanish *Príncipe de Asturias* design.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AV-8S Matador/Harrier STOVL fighter wing, mostly inoperable by 1999, was retired from service without replacement in 2006.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2010, the ship is used for helicopter operations and for disaster relief.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* is a 27,079-tonne amphibious assault ship (LHD) (outfitted as drone carrier) of the Turkish Navy that can be configured as a 24,660-tonne V/STOL aircraft carrier.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Construction began on 30 April 2016 by Sedef Shipbuilding Inc. at their Istanbul shipyard.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* was commissioned with a ceremony on 10 April 2023.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of a sister ship, to be named TCG *Trakya*, is currently being planned by the Turkish Navy.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Sikorsky S-70B Seahawk and the Bell AH-1 SuperCobra are the two main types of helicopters used on TCG *Anadolu*, with the occasional use of CH-47F Chinook helicopters of the Turkish Army during military exercises and operations.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AH-1W Super Cobras will eventually be complemented and replaced by the TAI T929 ATAK 2.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The jet-powered, low-observable drone Bayraktar MIUS Kızılelma and the MALE UAV Bayraktar TB3 are two UCAVs that are specifically designed and manufactured by Baykar Technologies to be used on TCG *Anadolu*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The maiden flight of TAI Anka-3 (also part of Project MIUS), a jet-powered, flying wing type UCAV with stealth technology, was successfully completed on 28 December 2023.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 19 November 2024, Baykar Bayraktar TB3 UCAV successfully took-off from the flight deck of TCG *Anadolu* and landed on the ship.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] It was the first time a fixed-wing unmanned aircraft of this size and class had successfully landed on a short-runway landing helicopter dock, without the use of an arresting gear.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 3 January 2024, the Turkish government approved the plan for the design and construction of a larger aircraft carrier, named the *MUGEM*-class.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 15 February 2024, the Design and Projects Office of the Turkish Navy announced that it will be a STOBAR aircraft carrier with an overall length of 285 metres (935 ft), beam of 72 metres (236 ft), draught of 10.1 metres (33 ft), and displacement of 60,000 tons.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is to have a combined diesel–electric and gas (CODLAG) propulsion system and a maximum speed of more than 25 knots (29 mph; 46 km/h).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of the first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier began on 2 January 2025.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier is being built at the Istanbul Naval Shipyard.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two 80,600-tonne (est. full load) *Queen Elizabeth*-class STOVL carriers which operate the F-35 Lightning II.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMS *Queen Elizabeth* was commissioned in December 2017 and HMS *Prince of Wales* in December 2019.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The current US fleet of *Nimitz*-class carriers will be followed into service (and in some cases replaced) by the *Gerald R.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is expected that the ships will be more automated in an effort to reduce the amount of funding required to maintain and operate the vessels.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The main new features are implementation of Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System (EMALS) (which replaces the old steam catapults) and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In terms of future carrier developments, Congress has discussed the possibility of accelerating the phasing-out of one or more *Nimitz*-class carriers, postponing or canceling the procurement of CVN-81 and CVN-82, or modifying the purchase contract.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Following the deactivation of USS *Enterprise* in December 2012, the US fleet comprised 10 fleet carriers, but that number increased back to 11 with the commissioning of *Gerald R.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The House Armed Services Seapower subcommittee on 24 July 2007, recommended seven or eight new carriers (one every four years).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] However, the debate has deepened over budgeting for the $12–14.5 billion (plus $12 billion for development and research) for the 100,000-tonne *Gerald R.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Ford*-class carrier (estimated service 2017) compared to the smaller $2 billion 45,000-tonne *America*-class amphibious assault ships, which are able to deploy squadrons of F-35Bs.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first of this class, USS *America*, is now in active service with another, USS *Tripoli*, and 9 more are planned.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In a report to Congress in February 2018, the Navy stated it intends to maintain a "12 CVN force" as part of its 30-year acquisition plan.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] A few aircraft carriers have been preserved as museum ships.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently portrayed in a number of Hollywood films including *Midway* (2019) and the carrier USS *Nimitz* is centrally featured in the science fiction film *The Final Countdown* (1980).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The original film version about the Battle at Midway was made in England and titled *Midway* (1976).
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently featured in both *Top Gun* and *Top Gun: Maverick* as providing the launch sites and mission operations support for the fighter operations seen in both films.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Japanese aircraft carriers involved in the attack on Pearl Harbor are featured in the 1970 film *Tora!
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] Tora!* as well as the more recent film from 2001 *Pearl Harbor*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier USS *Ronald Reagan* makes a cameo appearance at the end of the 2012 science fiction film *Battleship*.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] In the 2025 film *Mission: Impossible – The Final Reckoning*, the aircraft carrier USS *George Bush* is featured as delivering its special agent to a submarine rendezvous with the nuclear-powered USS *Ohio* in the Bering Straits by Alaska.
[src:compressor-stall/aircraft-carrier-p02] The 50-minute documentary titled *City of Steel: Carrier* was released by the Discovery Channel in 2000 covering the final months of building and inspecting the USS *Harry Truman* through its commissioning by President Bill Clinton.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] A **compressor stall** is a local disruption of the airflow in the compressor of a gas turbine or turbocharger.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] A stall that results in the complete disruption of the airflow through the compressor is referred to as a **compressor surge**.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The severity of the phenomenon ranges from a momentary power drop barely registered by the engine instruments to a complete loss of compression in case of a surge, requiring adjustments in the fuel flow to recover normal operation.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Modern compressors are carefully designed and controlled to avoid or limit stall within an engine's operating range.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] There are two types of compressor stall, described below.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The stall cells will affect subsequent airfoils around the rotor as each encounters the cell.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Propagation of the instability around the flow path annulus is driven by stall cell blockage causing an incidence spike on the adjacent blade.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The adjacent blade stalls as a result of the incidence spike, thus causing stall cell "rotation" around the rotor.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Stable local stalls can also occur which are axi-symmetric, covering the complete circumference of the compressor disc, but only a portion of its radial plane, with the remainder of the face of the compressor continuing to pass normal flow.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] A rotational stall may be momentary, resulting from an external disturbance, or may be steady as the compressor reaches a working equilibrium between stalled and unstalled areas.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Local stalls substantially reduce the efficiency of the compressor and increase the structural loads on the airfoils encountering stall cells in the region affected.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] In many cases however, the compressor airfoils are critically loaded without capacity to absorb the disturbance to normal airflow such that the original stall cells affect neighbouring regions and the stalled region rapidly grows to affect the entire compressor.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The compressor will recover to normal flow once the engine pressure ratio reduces to a level at which the compressor is capable of sustaining stable airflow.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] If, however, the conditions that induced the stall remain, the return of stable airflow will reproduce the conditions at the time of surge and the process will repeat.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] A compressor will only pump air in a stable manner up to a certain pressure ratio.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Beyond this value the flow will break down and become unstable.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] This occurs at what is known as the surge line on a compressor map.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The complete engine is designed to keep the compressor operating a small distance below the surge pressure ratio on what is known as the operating line on a compressor map.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The distance between the two lines is known as the surge margin on a compressor map.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Various things can occur during the operation of the engine to lower the surge pressure ratio or raise the operating pressure ratio.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] When the two coincide there is no longer any surge margin and a compressor stage can stall or the complete compressor can surge as explained in preceding sections.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The following, if severe enough, can cause stalling or surging.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Compressor axially-symmetric stalls, or compressor surges, are immediately identifiable, because they produce one or more extremely loud bangs from the engine.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Reports of jets of flame emanating from the engine are common during this type of compressor stall.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] These stalls may be accompanied by an increased exhaust gas temperature, an increase in rotor speed due to the large reduction in work done by the stalled compressor and — in the case of multi-engine aircraft — yawing in the direction of the affected engine due to the loss of thrust.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The appropriate response to compressor stalls varies according to the engine type and situation, but usually consists of immediately and steadily decreasing thrust on the affected engine.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] While modern engines with advanced control units can avoid many causes of stall, jet aircraft pilots must continue to take this into account when dropping airspeed or increasing throttle.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] A compressor anti-stall system is a compressor bleed system that automatically dumps away unwanted air to prevent compressor stalling.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Other methods of stall prevention may include an anti-stall tip treatment of the casing.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The Rolls-Royce Avon turbojet engine was affected by repeated compressor surges early in its 1940s development which proved difficult to eliminate from the design.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Such was the perceived importance and urgency of the engine that Rolls-Royce licensed the compressor design of the Sapphire engine from Armstrong Siddeley to speed development.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The engine, as redesigned, went on to power aircraft such as the English Electric Lightning fighter, English Electric Canberra bomber, and the de Havilland Comet and Sud Aviation Caravelle airliners.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] During the 1960s development of the Concorde Supersonic Transport (SST) a major incident occurred when a compressor surge caused a structural failure in the intake.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The hammershock which propagated forward from the compressor was of sufficient strength to cause an inlet ramp to become detached and expelled from the front of the intake.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The ramp mechanism was strengthened and control laws changed to prevent a re-occurrence.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] A compressor stall contributed to the 1994 death of Lt.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Kara Hultgreen, the first female carrier-based United States Navy fighter pilot.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The 1977 loss of Southern Airways Flight 242, a McDonnell Douglas DC-9-9-31, while penetrating a thunderstorm cell over Georgia, was attributed to compressor stalls brought on by ingestion of large quantities of water and hail.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The stalls caused blades to clash with stationary vanes in both of its Pratt & Whitney JT8D-9 turbofan engines.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The stalls were so severe as to cause the destruction of the engines, leaving the flight crew with no choice but to make an emergency landing on a public road, killing 62 passengers and another eight people on the ground.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] On December 6, 1997, an Antonov 124 transport plane was destroyed when it crashed immediately after takeoff from Irkutsk-2 Airport in Russia.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Three seconds after lifting off from Runway 14, at a height of about 5 metres (16 ft), the number 3 engine surged.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Climbing away with a high angle of attack, engines 1 and 2 also surged, causing the aircraft to crash some 1,600 metres (5,200 ft) past the end of the runway.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] It struck several houses in a residential area, killing all 23 on board, and 45 people on the ground.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] On November 6, 1967, TWA Flight 159, a Boeing 707 on its takeoff roll from the then-named Greater Cincinnati Airport, passed Delta Air Lines Flight 379, a McDonnell Douglas DC-9 stuck in the dirt a few feet off the runway's edge.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The first officer on the TWA aircraft heard a loud bang, now known to have been a compressor stall induced by ingestion of exhaust from Delta 379 as it was passed.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Believing a collision had occurred, the copilot aborted the takeoff.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Because of its speed, the aircraft overran the runway, injuring 11 of the 29 passengers, one of whom died four days later as a result of the injuries.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] In December 1991 Scandinavian Airlines System Flight 751, a McDonnell Douglas MD-81 on a flight from Stockholm to Copenhagen, crashed after losing both engines due to ice ingestion leading to compressor stall shortly after takeoff.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] Due to a newly installed auto-throttle system designed to prevent pilots reducing power during the takeoff climb, the pilot's commands to reduce power on recognising the surge were countermanded by the system, leading to engine damage and total engine failure.
[src:compressor-stall/compressor-stall] The airliner successfully made a forced landing in a forest clearing without loss of life.
